segments.text: You were saying that on, what was right here at the, I guess the east end of A&M, what was that like?
Was it, did it belong to the A&M campus?
Here where the golf course is, cows was there.
Well, the horse bond was up on the other side of the main building up here.
Mr. Garrigan was the horse man.
D.W. Williams was the head of the animal husbandry.
And all of that walk put down on the other side of the main building.
When the chemistry building was built, I remember that.
Well, did the hogs and the cows, were they used to feed people on campus, or was it more like an experiment station?
Well, I imagine they experimented on them, with them, and I imagine they killed some.
But it wasn't nothing but hogs.
They used to get all the garbage from the mess hole and feed those hogs.
Were hogs raised in the community around College Station?
Well, outlying people, like down on the other side of Washington Chapel.
All that land back down on the side of where you read them, that belonged to blacks.
There was black name after black name.
The land behind it was Richardson.
All the way back to the bypass.
Did they trade their crops with A&M, or did they take them into Bryan?
Had to take it to the gym.
Well crops that they raised, whatever vegetables.
Did they ever sell that to A&M College?
They raised just enough to supply the family.
Okay, but what they made their money from was cotton.
I guess we were also talking about Bryan, and you made a good point that the A&M College provided jobs for people who lived in Bryan.
Did Bryan, do you feel like they treated the people differently that lived around the college?
Because they felt like they had better paying jobs than the bribed.
So there was a sense of rivalry between the two people?
They just seemed as if they had a little more respect for the guys out here on the campus
Mr. Redwood beat up guys down in Brown.
And you're talking about all people.
You're not just talking about the black community?
Well, I can only answer for the black community.
Oh, OK. Because I didn't know too much about the white community in Brown.
But I knew about the white community here.
Well, the reason I was asking these questions is, you know, it could have easily have gone this way, that Bryan had incorporated this land into their city, and yet it didn't.
It became its own town, and I was just curious as to why that happened.
A person, at least I do, I feel like each individual would like something of their own.
And I can say, mine, when I come in.
I tell a lot of the students, you're not an Aggie.
So you just attended school here.
And I explained it to her.
You were going to Kyle Field.
But you know what I mean, until I really get serious.
Now, back to this town, Richardson, probably, down there, Washington Chapel.
He sold that land $200 an acre.
He could have got $200 a foot for it.
If you don't know, you don't know.
and you see something around the people, and you see around people all the time.
Also, when you were talking about Washington Chapel, you were saying an elementary school was there.
And how many grades did that serve?
Did you have to walk from A&M campus to there?
Well, a lot of people probably think that's pretty far today.
Did it meet all year long?
Did it meet all the nine months?
Was it a county school then?
Even when the weather was bad, you had to walk it.
And even if it was raining, you would just have to come wet.
Do you remember after Consolidated was built over here off the campus on the Hollick land, was there a black school that was also developed around there for the black children to go to?
On the harlot land, I wasn't there.
I was there when I was.
And you've heard of Lincoln Center and Lincoln School?
I knew all the harlots, the old ladies.
I knew all of them, the mama and the papa.
Well, can you tell me a little bit about that, the bohemian, bohemian?
You don't lie to them, you get along with them.
Tell them the truth, it's OK. Kopchinsky, right up there by the tower, he used to own that.
I'd sit down at his table so many times with him and his family.
They called him Mo-pop, or Mo-cop, and Po-cop.
And John Stastny down the lower, on the same side.
Victor Bariski on the other side had a chicken farm.
Were you familiar with the Krennicks?
How did you meet these people?
They... Well, just... Because they farmed, didn't they?
Did they come to A&M campus?
Well, Felix and I would work up there a week or two or something, you know, when he'd get caught up doing the construction work.
And Rick and I would work up there.
The old man John Stassman never did work.
Frank David Vaughan never did work, but he had 10 or 12 shotgun houses over there.
And what were the years of the shotgun houses?
Some of these men would come and work on campus, but you must have gotten off of campus and associated with them also.
That's where I met a lot of these people from the rural.
I mean, when I mean rural, I say, well, from around Rome, Chapel Weldon, or Berkshire.
I know more white people than every client.
When I started working at Standard Oil, I wasn't around nothing but Caucasian people.
I could shower in, Ali Khan, all that much.
I knew all of them personally.
Because of working with Standard Oil?
Talk with them just like I'm talking with you.
And then there's brothers and sisters, father, mother.
There's lots of different men in these.
What was the character of the town?
Apparently, it must have been very close-knit so that if you would go and eat with different families.
To carry yourself in a respectable way.
And he was alone with that children.
There's some, I won't name them.
Some of them are from Florida.
And if you work for them, come get your food out the back door you sit on the steps and eat.
If I call their name, you probably know them.
I love them, but how are you going to do that?
But for the most part, people were not like that.
Bolton, he lived in the kitchen.
But he up there in the dining room, he lived out here.
And just so many, I can't think of all of them.
Did Mr. Langford, he helped you provide financing for college.
Did he do this for other people, too?
It was just that they knew you because you lived on campus.
Were there other black children that grew up on campus with you?
I just guess they took a liking to me.
After he died, I never did go see her before she passed.
Not that I didn't want to, but I had a reason.
It didn't make sense for me to go there and break down.
When I ran into everybody, she would die.
When she had passed, I cried.
So apparently, Mr. Langford was a very wonderful person, very unique, very...
Well, his language was a prince.
You know, that's important because he was the mayor for so long, and he had such an influence on how College Station came to be.
So College Station was very lucky to have him as their mayor.
My mother worked raising these boys.
She worked for them all the time.
Do you like the way that College Station has developed?
Although I'm lost if I get up there.
But I can get down walking and, you know, find my way.
But in a car, one-way streets, you know, and all that, I guess I'll turn around.
Do you think it's growing too fast, or do you feel like that's the best for it?
Do you find that because it's gotten larger that you don't have that closeness between people?
That apparently you did when you were growing up here?
Oh, I don't know any of the people there now.
But now, I'll get on the telephone and call Mrs. Brass, Mrs. Walker.
She came over to Brian's and brought me some food.
No, she was buried in that.
And I had to stay there three weeks.
As long as I had ever stayed in there, I found out.
After your mother, I guess she had lived in the shotgun houses, did she move to Bryan later on?
Yes, and built a home and everything.
And still work as a domestic, or did she?
She used to come out here, buy a car, and work as a domestic.
R-H-O-N-E. R-H-O-N-E. Ms. Bryson knows her.
And I don't know if Ms. Wankler remembers her or not.
She's still someplace back over there.
I think they told me where that
someplace close to where Mr. Burgess used to live or live now.
I know where that is, Lee Street.
Lee Street is where Mr. Burgess lives.
Do you remember the, apparently there was some kind of rural housing for boys that really didn't have the money and they came and it was kind of a co-op housing.
But I think they were here.
I came here on a vacation.
I don't know what they were, but I think that's what it was.
I probably am forgetting a lot of things, but is there anything that you would like to add that maybe I haven't talked about?
And if you think of something else, well, you can get in touch with me.
OK. My main point was just to know what College Station was like when you were growing up here, and what the character of the town was.
I had more clothes then than I've gotten now.
Because did you get them from kids living on campus?
They would give you their clothes?
Did they give them to other black children, too?
If they knew them, they'd let them in the dormitory.
I made out of 20, 21 seeds of clove.
Did you take any of these and take them to your relatives in Navasota, like the food that we were talking about earlier?
Well, I didn't have any relatives.
I mean, my grandfather and things like that, you know.
Or any of the other kids?
I didn't, you know, other people.
I couldn't eat all of it.
So you also gave them away to people in the community.
So it helped not only you, but others.
Well, they didn't have the opportunity to go.
Well, you had such an interesting upbringing, being on the campus, being a part of everything, being part of the core activities.
And you went to the football games.
Never paid to go to a football game in life.
Any time they had any kind of support?
Dick Carr and all that group.
I imagine they had any someplace.
So for your recreation, you would go and watch the Aggies play sports.
And for your own involvement, you and other blacks would play against, form your own teams?
Were these kids that lived on the campus or kids you went to school with?
Around the campus, you know, in walking distance, around hot liquor stores, places like that.
I talked to Mr. Krennic, and he said he's older than you are, I believe.
But he said that they played basketball.
I used to go up to the country club and carry.
I really didn't like it, so I didn't play much other than baseball and football.
Well, is there anything else you'd like to add?
Well, I appreciate you having this interview with me.
It certainly helped me a lot in writing.
I'm glad I'll be able to help you.
And those pictures there, after you have them blowed up, you can mail them to me.
I'll mail these, and I'll mail a blown-up picture, too.
